# Damage {#damage}

Natural hazards caused damage ever since humans settled in the alps, as the Goldau Landslide from 1806 impressively shows, when a whole village was covered in debris and over 450 people died (Reynard 2025). Since 1946 the yearly causalties are reported on national level. 




Although there is a huge variability in the number of yearly causalties, since 1946 a overall decline can be observed. While in the 1960s on average 5 people per year died due to gravitational natural hazards 
In comparison to for example Typhoons, tsunamis, earthquakes or volcanism in other countries and regions of the world, the overall number of causalties with 667 since 1946 is quite low in Switzerland. 

Switzerland is a safe country and is capable of reducing the number of deaths due to gravitational hazards since 1946. Considering both a significant increase in rockfall activity (PERMOS 2025) and in population, the decline in causalties is a huge success for natural hazard management in Switzerland. 


