      text: "Glaciers are in danger. Until 2100 under high emission scenarios, even the largest glaciers might almost be gone. Regardless of the climate scenario till 2050 small glaciers with accumulation areas beneath 3400m will be gone (Dumeont et al.). On average in the past 50 years alpine glaciers lost 40 % of their area. Like permafrost, glaciers are acting as stabilisiers of sediment and slopes. Unconsolidated debris beneath the current glaciers are getting exposed  (Dumont et al. 2025)."
    },
    muren: {
      title: "Debris flows",
      text: "When the hole streambed gets mobilized a stream of water, air,  and fines rushes downwards and puts lifes, homes and livelihoods in danger (Qie 2023). Typically such events are triggered by high rainfall intensity. Permafrost thaw, decreased sediment cohesion and the increase in high intensity precipitation events contribute to growing frequencies and magnitude of debris flows in the future (Dumont et al. 2025). Especially regions with current permafrost degradation and unlimited sediment supply will experience a significant increase of debris flows (Moser 2025). In catchments with limited sediment supply, no significant change can be determined, although rainfall intensities increase (Brunner 2024)."
